Don't you hate that you finally get to see the doctor and they don't give you time to explain EVERYTHING that's wrong? 

They cut you off or dismiss your pain? Yes doctors are busy and have to jump from room to room but that doesn't mean that you are important too! I found ways where I can communicate better with my doctor and they know that when I get their attention they are going to stay there. 

How you ask? I try to treat them like a human being and not like a robot. I know that this sometimes may not work but I also ask them how they're doing too because they are people with feelings and they will not always have all the answers. But I know it is frustrating and all have experienced this one time or another.

Comment below if this has happened to you! 👇👇👇

Today’s Stronger Than Autoimmune podcast episode features Shamikka Marty aka PrettySickLupusChick. She currently resides in Bay Area, California but is originally from New Jersey. She lives with her husband of 18 years, Henry and has 3 beautiful children Amaru, Alejandra and Antonio plus her 2 puppies Luna and Lilo. She graduated from Williamstown High School and earned her degree in International Business from Rutgers University. She then ventured to obtain her certification in Project Management, Scrum Master and Cybersecurity from Rutgers School of Business.

She currently works as a Cybersecurity Project Manager, Motivational Speaker, Social Media Influencer for Chronic Illness, Board member for several Organizations (Lupus Foundation of America SF, Lupus Foundation of Northern California, Director for Yathom Foundation, Rotary Club of Dublin, Paramedic Advisory Board of Northern CA, Assistance League of Amador Valley and more). She has overcome adversity since she was 10, taking care of her nana who had severe RA (bedridden for 20 yrs), her single mother who had Lupus, her uncle who has HIV. So her whole life has been apart of the chronic ill life since birth spending 2 years in the NICU for the first 2 months of her life due to heart complications as a preemie.

She was diagnosed with Lupus herself at age 30 along with several overlapping auto immune diseases (RA, MCTD, Raynaud’s, Sjogren’s, Scleroderma, Vasculitis, CKD, IBS, Endometriosis). She was blessed to receive a kidney transplant in 2023. All of her pain pushes her to keep moving forward and inspire others in person and especially on social media.

Follow her to see the good, bad and ugly on IG, TikTok and Facebook under @prettysicklupuschick

Visiting a Theme Park while being chronically ill. I recently went to Universal Studios and I've been to several parks like Disneyland and World. I always see people who are disabled not utilizing the accommodations for them or bringing the right stuff. Did you know you don't have to wait in the long lines? You don't have to purchase their express pass? Just contact the park in advance. Look on their website for ADA accomodations. Save yourself the pain and it's ok that you don't have a visible illness some just ask for a doctor's note or nothing at all. Remember to live life and have fun.

Mental health matters! Happy World Mental Health Day! People don't talk about how having illness affects your mental health. I definitely don't put rainbows and sunshine everyday. Life itself can be depressing and add going through chronic illness or disease makes it difficult. You see me out even when I'm in extreme pain because laying down makes me depressed. I know my body needs to heal sometimes but when I stay still all the pain comes stronger. I tend to have negative thoughts like this body is junk. We need to remember we are worthy and stuff as nails! But when you can't please talk to someone, get help. It's ok not to be ok sometimes.

It's that time of year! Halloween! 🎃

Like, share, leave a comment if you agree that living with an invisible chronic illness can feel incredibly isolating and tway scarier than 👻 and haunted houses. 

I like to utilize my page as a platform for everyone to be able to feel less alone. To see someone that has what they have and is trying to plow through the good, the bad, and the ugly. 

It is tough going through searching for answers getting blood work done, treatments 💉, and testing. At least you know I am going through it with you! 

We all deserve love we all deserve kindness. We all deserve understanding. Having an incurable illness does not mean unmanageable, so we must keep fighting for answers! Keep fighting for a cure, look for relief remedies, any glimmer of hope! 

Tag a friend and spread awareness! Reach out and check on your spoonie friends today! 💜💜

New Lupus Treatment Trials! 

➡️Do you know about Car T Cell Therapy? It's not just for cancer patients anymore!

➡️How do we get closer to a cure? By participating drug trials! 

➡️We need more diversity in these drug trials and I am trying to get the word out there. Black and Hispanic people are more impacted by Lupus and the least amount to volunteer for drug trials. 

➡️We need that to change as we see a lot of the treatments out there affect us differently or help at all. That's why I'm advocating for all to help with volunteering for our cause. We want better options and ultimately a CURE!

➡️ Please read, share the info above and see how you can join. Kyverna Therapeutics is one of many pharmaceutical companies that is paving the way to help autoimmune diseases. 

➡️If you have Lupus SLE, Nephritis, Multiple Sclerosis, then ask your doctor if this drug trial is safe for you to join. I've personally sat in on the talks for this treatment which is a one time infusion. 

➡️The results are promising. I don't just talk the talk I walk the walk. I'm signing up for a drug trial too. 

⭐Please comment below 👇 your thoughts, concerns or questions. Id love to hear from you. What's your hesitation or thoughts on drug trials? Let's all be apart of change!

#JanssenPartner | In my opinion, when living with #ChronicIllnesses like #Scleroderma, a disease that affects the skin, internal organs, and connective tissue, and #PulmonaryArterialHypertension (#PAH), a form of high blood pressure that impacts the arteries in the lungs, the most important thing is being your own advocate. Do the research. Take care of your mental health. Find support groups in real life or online. Make self-care a priority.

If you’re living with scleroderma like me, make sure to ask your doctor about screening for PAH. PAH is a #RareDisease, but Black women with scleroderma are at a higher risk of developing it and identifying the condition early is key to treating it. 

I know how lonely and challenging it can feel to live with chronic illnesses but remember that there are resources out there. If you want to learn more about PAH, visit the link in my bio.

Attended the ONC Meeting in DC where the focus was improving Interoperability aka Patient Access. What does that mean to you? Big steps towards making sure your medical records are accessible to you and all of your providers. As more and more physicians and medical facilities upgrade their technology we still incur impediments with data sharing. 

Ever go to one specialist and they request a test that you recently done, want to prove your medical history but they can't see it? Well that's what they are trying to provide and set standards on protecting your data. Sounds minor but this huge. Being able to provide a chronic illness prospective into what we actually need is key. They do this as a job but this is our lives! I'm small but mighty. 

We still have a ways to go like making this international and many other initiatives but one small step for accessibility! Please let me what you think? What else should we consider regarding access? Check out the ONC website. The office of National Coordinator for Healthcare IT. Look them up for the latest news!

44 years around the sun and I'm far from done. Just a quick recap of my amazing birthday weekend! It's not just a number for me. I've had in my head for years since my mom passed away from lupus after her kidney rejected after 7 years at age 44, I thought will I make it?

 She only got to experience one month of 44. I made it. I had my transplant 11 months ago and she showed me how to survive with her sickness. She showed me how to be strong. I am truly grateful for my blessings and my struggles. They make me. My upbringing humbles me. Not having her here drives me to make sure I'm here for my kids. Thank you to everyone for making this birthday special and being there for me. Thank you toy husband for volunteering to give up his kidney to get me to the top of the list. And as a NYE baby wishing you all a better Happy New Year!

Together is the first app to use generative AI to make cumbersome healthcare tasks ‘magically easy’. 

🌟@togetherbyrenee removes the barriers between aging Americans and better health by helping patients and caregivers manage their medications, appointments, refills, doctors and more — with no typing — just using their smartphone camera and voice.

🌟-Dr. Renee Dua and Nick Desai — who previously founded and built visionary doctor house call company Heal — today introduced Together by Renee, the first app to use generative AI to complete and manage cumbersome healthcare tasks for aging adults, those with chronic diseases and their overwhelmed caregivers. Together requires no typing or data entry and uses just the smartphone camera and AI to “magically” remove the myriad obstacles — such as medication refills, scheduling appointments, complex forms, opaque insurance benefits and more — that stand between Americans over 50 and better health outcomes.

🌟In fact, Together is the first U.S. app that measures vitals including blood pressure, heart rate, heart rate variability, respiratory rate and blood oxygen just by having users smile for a selfie, a breakthrough in ease and usability. This deviceless, hassle-free “always with you” ability to track vitals is invaluable both for those with chronic diseases and worried caregivers, who can make sure their loved ones are doing well from far away.

🌟 Available on iPhone only at this time coming soon to Android.

New Year New Bills! Effective January 1st in California is AB 248 Individuals with disabilities. 

☑️The Dignity for All Act.

☑️Existing law includes the terms “mentally retarded persons,” “mentally retarded children,” “retardation,” and “handicap."

☑️This bill, The Dignity for All Act, would make nonsubstantive changes to those provisions to eliminate this obsolete terminology. 

☑️The bill would repeal obsolete provisions of law.
